  {
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> Why does the getCurrentRefinements returns something that looks like a promise?\n\nSo all the utils are just returning the global \"browser\" variable created by webdriver.io, it represents the currently opened browser and you access all the API methods from http://webdriver.io/api.html\n\nBut it's also a sort of magic promise chain so that after each command you can use .then() to check the results.\n\n> How does getCurrentRefinements get the state?\n\nHere's the implementation:\n\n``` js\nexport function getCurrentRefinements() {\n  return browser\n    .element('#current-refined-values .item')\n    .then(() => browser\n      .getText('#current-refined-values .item')\n      .then(res => {\n        return res.map(refinement => {\n          const data = refinement.split('\\n');\n          const out = {\n            name: data[0]\n          };\n\n          if (data[1] !== undefined) {\n            out.count = parseInt(data[1], 10);\n          }\n\n          return out;\n        });\n      })\n    )\n    .catch(() => Promise.resolve([]));\n}\n```\n\nSo it's pretty raw but does the job.\n\n> I'm already loving it :) I'm going to have some fun with it this afternoon (CET :))\n\nIf you already want to add new tests: AWESOME. Here's what you can do:\n- install the https://github.com/elgalu/docker-selenium thing\n- run it like this:\n\n``` sh\ndocker run --net=\"host\" --rm --name=grid -e VNC_PASSWORD=fun -e NOVNC=true elgalu/selenium:2.48.2k\n```\n- try to access in a browser in osx: http://localhost:6080/vnc.html and use password fun, you should see the underlying linux desktop\n- once you are here, take this current branch, npm install, npm run test:functional\n",
    "created_at": "2016-01-20T16:35:46Z",
